Roosevelt Avenue, at the southwest corner of Queens Boulevard, showing a group of buildings demolished in 1925, because they stood directly in the center of the new Queens Boulevard line. J. Burroughs owned the large building in 1860, while the little house; one and one half story; may have been the house of J. Smith in that year. In 1873 J. W. Burroughs operated the Central Hotel in the house in the foreground; in 1874 it was Hownes Hotel. Hugh O'Reilly had it in 1922 when it was known as the Wayside Inn.

1922

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Queens Boulevard (in center thereof), just east of Greenpoint Ave. This property was just east of an old hotel operated by Hugh O'Reilly which in 1891 was located at the intersection of Thompson Ave. (now Queens Boulevard) and Greenpoint Ave. The group of buildings which may have belonged to Mrs. Cameron in 1873 were demolished in March 1925. In the left background is an elevated line known as the Flushing Elevated Lines and is operated by the Manhattan and Queens County Railway Company.

March 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
